title: Public Records Request for Bodycam Footage, Dashcam, and Reports – Arrest of Domanie Chandon Roberts (07/30/2023)

communications.subject: Georgia Open Records Act Request: Public Records Request for Bodycam Footage, Dashcam, and Reports – Arrest of Domanie Chandon Roberts (07/30/2023)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Georgia Open Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

I request access to the following records related to the arrest of Domanie Chandon Roberts, 40 at the time, which occurred on July 30, 2023, at approximately 10:13 PM in the 600 block of Vallotton Dr., Valdosta, GA:

Body-worn camera footage from all officers involved in the traffic stop, physical altercation, and arrest of Domanie Chandon Roberts.
Incident report(s) and arrest report(s) related to this case (Report #23-7398).
Dashcam footage from any patrol units that conducted the traffic stop or were involved in the response.
Rear-seat police vehicle footage (if applicable) from the unit that transported Mr. Roberts following his arrest.
This request is focused on essential records that document the escalation of a routine traffic stop into a physical confrontation. If any 911 calls or additional footage (such as surveillance) exist, I request them only if they provide significant additional context to the events.

Fee Waiver Request
I request a fee waiver as the release of these records serves the public interest by providing transparency regarding law enforcement actions and the use of force.

Please provide these records in digital format via email or a secure online portal if available. If any associated fees apply, please inform me before processing. If any portion of this request is denied or redacted, please cite the specific exemption under Georgia law.

Thank you for your time and assistance. Please confirm receipt of this request at your earliest convenience.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 3 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Police Cam News

communications.subject: RE: Georgia Open Records Act Request: Public Records Request for Bodycam Footage, Dashcam, and Reports – Arrest of Domanie Chandon Roberts (07/30/2023)

Respectfully,

communications.subject: RE: Georgia Open Records Act Request: Public Records Request for Bodycam Footage, Dashcam, and Reports – Arrest of Domanie Chandon Roberts (07/30/2023)
communications.communication:
I have just heard back from State Court about the adjudication status of the case.  I have forwarded the request to the Digital Media Tech and P&E tech to see if they have any photos/videos for this case.

You requested that we notify you before processing if there would be any associated fees.  There will be fees of 50¢ per cd (will not be sent electronically) or between $5-10 for a thumb drive (depending on how much video/photos may be available the information might have to be put on a thumb drive).  You will also incur charges of $12 per hour (1st 15 mins are free) for the copying of any videos/photos and other material being copied/printed.  You requested incident/arrest reports, so that would incur a charge of 10¢ per page, which stands @ 9 pgs or 90¢.  Finally you will have charges for postage between 70¢ and $2.00 (depending on what is being released).

Low end estimate w/ cd(s):
$7.50

High end estimate w/ thumb drive:
$25.00

Please let me know if you would like to continue with the request.

Respectfully,
Tonya Kennedy

communications.subject: California Public Records Act Request: Field Interview Cards (Riverside County Sheriff)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the California Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

Hello, 

I am requesting copies of blank field interview cards or equivalent forms filled out during a police stop. Search 2018 to 2024, if there have been no changes since 2018 to the cards, then that year is sufficient. 

Thank you

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 calendar days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Joey Scott

communications.subject: Nevada Public Records Act Request: Nevada Inmates Wages While Fighting Fires
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Nevada Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

1). The number of inmates/offenders from the Nevada Department of Corrections that received training to fight wildfires from January 2019 - December 2024, and the total costs associated with that program. 
2). The wages of Nevada inmates/offenders for that were fighting fires from January 2019-December 2024, including information on race, age, gender and convicted crime but eliminating other private information.
3). The amount of money received into the Division of Forestry Account as outlined in NRS 209.231, reflecting money which is obtained from the operation of a conservation camp and which is not used for salaries, overhead or operating expenses of any conservation camp is required to be deposited in the Division of Forestry Account. 
4). The State Forestry Firewarden's determination of wages that must be paid to inmates/ offenders in the years 2019-2024 in accordance to  NRS 472.040h.
5). The contract between California Division of Forestry and the Nevada Department of Corrections pertaining to financial agreements for use of Nevada's Inmates / Offenders from January 2019-December 2024.
6). All contracts and bills from the Humboldt Conservation Camp regarding the 2011 "general clean up" cooperated by a Stor-Al location in Winnemuca as found in Appendix A in https://www.leg.state.nv.us/Division/Audit/Full/BE2014/Division%20of%20Forestry,%20LA14-01%20Full.pdf

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

michelle baker

communications.subject: Muckrock Request Response
communications.communication:
Hello Ms. Baker,

   Nevada Division of Forestry is in receipt of your public records requests originating on 3/6/25. Below and attached constitutes our response accordingly.


  1.  The number of inmates/offenders from Nevada Department of Corrections that received training to fight wildfires from January 2019-December 2024, and the total costs associated with that program.

Agency Response:  4,509 inmates/offenders were trained by Nevada Division of Forestry during this time period to fight wildfires. NDF does not track the costs associated with this training program specifically so a total cost is not available.


  1.  The wages of Nevada inmates/offender that were fighting fires from January 2019-December 2024, including information on race, age, gender, and convicted crime, but eliminating other private information.

Agency Response: The wage for inmate/offender firefighters regardless of race, age, gender and convicted crime is $1/hr for 24hrs/day while assigned to a fire. NDF does not receive or track any data related to inmate/offender race, age, gender, and convicted crime and therefore cannot produce this information.


  1.  The amount of money received in the Nevada Division of Forestry account as outlined in NRS 209.231, reflecting money which is obtained from the operation of a conservation camp and which is not used for salaries, overhead or operating expenses of any conservation camp is required to be deposited in the Division of Forestry account.

Agency Response: There are no funds received from the operation of conservation camps in excess of those used for salaries, overhead or operating expenses.


  1.  The Forester Firewarden determination of wages that must paid to inmates/offenders in the years 2019-2024 in accordance to NRS 472.040h.

Agency Response: Please see .pdfs attached with determinations and rate sheets.


  1.  The contract between California Division of Forestry and the Nevada Department of Corrections pertaining to financial agreements for use of Nevada's inmates/offenders from January 2019-December 2024.

Agency Response: Nevada Division of Forestry does not track contracts between California Division of Forestry and Nevada Department of Corrections. This request should be re-directed by the requestor to either of those entities.


  1.  All contracts and bills from the Humboldt Conservation Camp regarding the 2011 "general clean up" cooperated by a Stor-All location in Winnemucca as found in Appendix A in Division of forestry, LA14-01 full.pdf<https://www.leg.state.nv.us/Division/audit/full/BE2014/Division%20of%20forestry,%20LA14-01%20full.pdf>

Agency Response: Due to the State of Nevada General Records Retention Schedule Version, dated 02/12/2025*, NDF does not have any previous contracts and or billing invoices from the Humboldt Conservation camp regarding the 2011 "general clean up" work performed for Stor-Al Winnemucca location.

This concludes the agency's response to the Muchrock public information request dated 3/6/25.

Sincerely,
Ryan

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: Farias-Farias Mortality Review
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

A copy of the IHSC Mortality Review for Edixon Del Jesus Farias Farias who died in ICE Custody April 18, 2024, according to the Detainee Death Report ICE published: https://www.ice.gov/doclib/foia/reports/ddrFarias-FariasEdixondelJesus.pdf

I make this request as a member of the media, and therefore seek a fee waiver. Representative edited works based on prior FOIA requests like this one may be reviewed here: https://theappeal.org/authors/andrew-free/; and here: https://atlpresscollective.com/2025/01/31/new-record-sheds-light-on-unreported-death-in-atlanta-airport-customs-inspection/. 

I request expedited processing of this request pursuant to 6 CFR 5.5(e) and attest under penalty of perjury pursuant to 28 USC 1746 that the following statements are true and correct to the best of my knowledge and understanding: 
1. ICE deaths in custody in FY25 are currently on track to equal or surpass the 12 deaths in the previous fiscal year. 

2. IHSC Mortality Reviews provide an authoritative agency accounting of the medical circumstances of in-custody deaths. These reviews often conflict with the public-facing story the agency tells, raising critical questions about accountability, transparency, waste, fraud, and abuse. See https://phr.org/our-work/resources/deadly-failures-preventable-deaths-in-u-s-immigration-detention/.

3. The current administration's expansion of federal immigration detention is the subject of widespread and exceptional media interest in which there exist possible questions about the government's integrity which affect public confidence. See, e.g., 
a. https://www.newyorker.com/news/the-lede/how-many-immigrants-will-die-in-us-custody

communications.subject: ICE FOIA 2025-ICFO-25067
communications.communication:
03/13/2025 

Andrew  Free 
MuckRock News, DEPT MR182991 
Boston, Massachusetts 02115 

RE:	ICE FOIA Case Number 2025-ICFO-25067 
 
Dear Requester: 

This acknowledges receipt of your Freedom of Information Act (FOIA) request to U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement (ICE), dated 3/13/2025, your request for a waiver of all assessable FOIA fees, and your request for expedited treatment. Your request was received in this office on 3/13/2025. Specifically, you have requested records pertaining to a copy of the IHSC Mortality Review for Edixon Del Jesus Farias Farias who died in ICE Custody April 18, 2024, according to the Detainee Death Report ICE published: https://www.ice.gov/doclib/foia/reports/ddrFarias-FariasEdixondelJesus.pdf. 

Due to the increasing number of FOIA requests received by this office, we may encounter some delay in processing your request. Per Section 5.5(a) of the DHS FOIA regulations, 6 C.F.R. Part 5, ICE processes FOIA requests according to their order of receipt. Although ICE’s goal is to respond within 20 business days of receipt of your request, the FOIA does permit a 10-day extension of this time period. As your request seeks numerous documents that will necessitate a thorough and wide-ranging search, ICE will invoke a 10-day extension for your request, as allowed by Title 5 U.S.C. § 552(a)(6)(B). If you’re able to narrow the scope of your request please contact our office. Narrowing the scope may speed up the search process. We will make every effort to comply with your request in a timely manner. 

Your request for expedited treatment is hereby denied. 

Under the DHS FOIA regulations, expedited processing of a FOIA request is warranted if the request involves “circumstances in which the lack of expedited treatment could reasonably be expected to pose an imminent threat to the life or physical safety of an individual,” 6 C.F.R. § 5.5(e)(1)(i), or “an urgency to inform the public about an actual or alleged federal government activity, if made by a person primarily engaged in disseminating information,” 6 C.F.R. § 5.5(e)(l)(ii).  Requesters seeking expedited processing must submit a statement explaining in detail the basis for the request, and that statement must be certified by the requester to be true and correct.  6 C.F.R. § 5.5(e)(3). 

Your request for expedited processing is denied because you do not qualify for either category under 6 C.F.R. § 5.5(e)(1).  You failed to demonstrate a particular urgency to inform the public about the government activity involved in the request beyond the public’s right to know about government activity generally.  Your letter was conclusory in nature and did not present any facts to justify a grant of expedited processing under the applicable standards. 

After thoroughly reviewing your letter and request for fee waiver, I have determined that you have not presented a convincing argument that you and/or your organization is entitled to a blanket waiver of applicable fees. 

The DHS FOIA Regulations at 6 CFR § 5.11(k)(2) set forth six factors to examine in determining whether the applicable legal standard for a fee waiver has been met.  We will consider these factors in our evaluation of your request for a fee waiver: 

(1) Whether the subject of the requested records concerns “the operations or activities of the government”; 
(2) Whether the disclosure is “likely to contribute” to an understanding of government operations or activities; 
(3) Whether disclosure of the requested information will contribute to the understanding of the public at large, as opposed to the individual understanding of the requestor or a narrow segment of interested persons; 
(4) Whether the contribution to public understanding of government operations or activities will be "significant"; 
(5) Whether the requester has a commercial interest that would be furthered by the requested disclosure; and 
(6) Whether the magnitude of any identified commercial interest to the requestor is sufficiently large in comparison with the public interest in disclosure, that disclosure is primarily in the commercial interest of the requestor. 

As a requester, you bear the burden under FOIA of showing that the fee waiver requirements have been met.  Based on my review of your 3/13/2025 letter and for the reasons stated herein, I have determined that your fee waiver request is deficient because your request did not satisfy factors 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, and 6. Since your request for a fee waiver has failed to satisfy each of the required factors, I am denying your fee waiver request. 

Provisions of the FOIA allow us to recover part of the cost of complying with your request.  We shall charge you for records in accordance with the DHS Interim FOIA regulations, as they apply to media requesters.  As a media requester, you will be charged 10 cents per page for duplication; the first 100 pages are free.  We will construe the submission of your request as an agreement to pay up to $25.00. You will be contacted before any further fees are accrued. 

If you deem the decision to deny expedited treatment and fee waiver for your request an adverse determination, you have the right to appeal.  Should you wish to do so, you must send your appeal and a copy of this letter, within 90 days of the date of this letter following the procedures outlined in the DHS FOIA regulations at 6 C.F.R. Part 5 § 5.5(e)(2). You may submit your appeal electronically at GILDFOIAAppeals@ice.dhs.gov or via regular mail to: 

U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement 
Office of the Principal Legal Advisor 
U.S. Department of Homeland Security 
500 12th Street,, S.W., Mail Stop 5900 
Washington, D.C. 20536-5900 

Your envelope and letter should be marked “FOIA Appeal.”  Copies of the FOIA and DHS regulations are available at www.dhs.gov/foia. 

ICE has queried the appropriate program offices within ICE for responsive records. If any responsive records are located, they will be reviewed for determination of releasability. Please be assured that one of the processors in our office will respond to your request as expeditiously as possible. We appreciate your patience as we proceed with your request. 

If you have any questions please contact FOIA Public Liaison Daniel Edgington, at (866) 633-1182 or 500 12th St, SW Stop 5009 Washington, DC 20536-5009. Additionally, you have a right to seek dispute resolution services from the Office of Government Information Services (OGIS) which mediates disputes between FOIA requesters and Federal agencies as a non-exclusive alternative to litigation.  If you are requesting access to your own records (which is considered a Privacy Act request), you should know that OGIS does not have the authority to handle requests made under the Privacy Act of 1974.  You may contact OGIS as follows:  Office of Government Information Services, National Archives and Records Administration, 8601 Adelphi Road-OGIS, College Park, Maryland 20740-6001, e-mail at ogis@nara.gov; telephone at 202-741-5770; toll free at 1-877-684-6448. 

Your request has been assigned reference number 2025-ICFO-25067. Please use this number in future correspondence. 
Sincerely, 

ICE FOIA Office 
Immigration and Customs Enforcement 
Freedom of Information Act Office 
500 12th Street, S.W., Stop 5009 
Washington, D.C. 20536-5009

communications.subject: ICE FOIA 2024-ICFO-05571
communications.communication:
11/13/2023Brandon GalbraithMuckRock News, DEPT MR154296Boston, Massachusetts 02115RE:	ICE FOIA Case Number 2024-ICFO-05571        Dear Requester:This acknowledges receipt of your 11/7/2023, Freedom of Information Act (FOIA) request to U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement (ICE), for policy for ICE issued mobile devices.  Your request was received in this office on 11/7/2023.Due to the increasing number of FOIA requests received by this office, we may encounter some delay in processing your request. Per Section 5.5(a) of the DHS FOIA regulations, 6 C.F.R. Part 5, ICE processes FOIA requests according to their order of receipt. Although ICE’s goal is to respond within 20 business days of receipt of your request, the FOIA does permit a 10-day extension of this time period. As your request seeks numerous documents that will necessitate a thorough and wide-ranging search, ICE will invoke a 10-day extension for your request, as allowed by Title 5 U.S.C. § 552(a)(6)(B). If you’re able to narrow the scope of your request please contact our office. Narrowing the scope may speed up the search process. We will make every effort to comply with your request in a timely manner.Provisions of the FOIA allow us to recover part of the cost of complying with your request.  We shall charge you for records in accordance with the DHS Interim FOIA regulations, as they apply to media requesters.  As a media requester, you will be charged 10 cents per page for duplication; the first 100 pages are free.  We will construe the submission of your request as an agreement to pay up to $25.00. You will be contacted before any further fees are accrued.We have queried the appropriate program offices within ICE for responsive records. If any responsive records are located, they will be reviewed for determination of releasability. Please be assured that one of the processors in our office will respond to your request as expeditiously as possible. We appreciate your patience as we proceed with your request.If you have any questions, please contact FOIA Public Liaison, Fernando Pineiro Jr. at the address above or (866) 633-1182. Additionally, you have a right to seek dispute resolution services from the Office of Government Information Services (OGIS) which mediates disputes between FOIA requesters and Federal agencies as a non-exclusive alternative to litigation. U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement 
Office of the Principal Legal Advisor 
U.S. Department of Homeland Security 
500 12th Street, S.W., Mail Stop 5900 
Washington, D.C. 20536-5900 

Your envelope and letter should be marked “FOIA Appeal.”  Copies of the FOIA and DHS regulations are available at www.dhs.gov/foia. 

Provisions of FOIA allow DHS to charge for processing fees, up to $25, unless you seek a waiver of fees.  In this instance, because the cost is below the $25 minimum, there is no charge. 

If you need any further assistance or would like to discuss any aspect of your request, please contact FOIA Public Liaison Daniel Edgington at (866) 633-1182 or 500 12th St. SW Stop 5009 Washington, DC 20536-5009. title: Request to DoD for all communications with producer Jerry Bruckheimer over last 20 years

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: Request to DoD for all communications with actor/director Jerry Bruckheimer over last 20 years
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

All communications between the Department of Defense (DoD) and the Hollywood producer and media executive Jerry Bruckheimer (born Jerome Leon Bruckheimer on September 21, 1943, in Detroit, Michigan), within the 20-year record retention schedule for such records (as specified on p. 202 of the May 2022 DoD document titled "Records Disposition Schedules," Record Group 303). Such communications may include, but should not be limited to, emails, correspondence, memos, and transcriptions of telephone calls.

I am the Director of Research Operations at a 501(c)(3) non-profit organization called The Decoding Culture Foundation. These documents will be used for public education and research purposes. I therefore request a waiver of all fees that may otherwise apply. Attached is a document with organization letterhead confirming my position, as well as the organization's 501(c)(3) application and approval form.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Brett Carollo

Nikky Southerland

RE: Public Disclosure Request#: P064472-092320 
 
Dear Nikky Southerland, 
 
Your third installment of records have been released and are available on the Public Records Request Center to download.  
At this time, the Seattle Police Department will have your next installment of records to you on 3/3/2022. 
To download your records, please: 
 
  * Navigate to the Public Records Request Center.
  * Select 'My Records Request Center'. 
  * Select 'View My Requests'. You may be asked to login. 
  * Select this request: P064472-092320. 
  * Select the 'View Files' button. 
  * You can download records individually or all at the same time by clicking 'Download All'. 
  *  Please save your records as you may only download them from the system three times. If you do not download your records within 30 days of request closure, the link to your records will expire. 
If you believe you have received privileged or confidential records in error, please notify the City of Seattle immediately, through the Public Records Request Center or by email. Privileged or confidential records provided or received in error should not be reviewed, used, disseminated, distributed, or copied, and should be destroyed immediately. Thank you in advance for your cooperation. 
 
If you have any questions, you may send a message using the Police Records Request Center or call the Public Disclosure Desk at 206-684-5481. 
 
Sincerely, 
Dianalynn Oreiro 
Seattle Police Department 
Legal Unit 
 
SPD receives between 7000 and 8000 public records requests annually and is processing more than 2000 open requests at a time. This may result in a slower than anticipated response to your request. Thank you for your patience. 
 
As a reminder you can login at the Police Records Request Center where you can access Police online information, manage your profile, submit record requests, track your request status, receive and send messages, make payments, view frequently asked questions, and download your records. 
 Please add seattle@mycusthelp.net to your E-mail contacts/address book to ensure delivery of the record center E-mails to your Inbox. (mailto:seattle@mycusthelp.net)

communications.subject: North Carolina Public Records Law Request: Third Party Investigative Platform (Purchase and Contract records) (Asheville Police Department)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the North Carolina Public Records Law, I hereby request the records listed below regarding the following four software programs: 

• Thompson Reuters Clear (https://legal.thomsonreuters.com/en/products/clear)
• LexisNexis Accurint (https://www.accurint.com/)
• TransUnion TLOxp, which may also be part of the TruLookup system (https://www.tlo.com/law-enforcement)
• SoundThinking CrimeTracer, which was formerly a product called COPLINK X (https://www.soundthinking.com/law-enforcement/crime-analysis-crimetracer/) from the company formerly known as ShotSpotter

For each of the above mentioned platforms, please provide the following records: 

• CONTRACTS AND AGREEMENTS —  All contracts (as well as associated amendments, attachments, and exhibits) and agreements related to the acquisition and use of these "software" programs.
• PURCHASE INFORMATION — All invoices and purchase information for costs and products associated with the above-referenced platforms.

Please provide responsive materials for the period from January 1, 2021 through the date this request is processed. 

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days.

Sincerely,

Beryl Lipton

title: Library Contract Request: Wiley Online Library at Bowie State University

communications.subject: Maryland Public Information Act Request: Library Contract Request: Wiley Online Library at Bowie State University
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Maryland Public Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

The most recent contract, governing, base, or master license agreement with John Wiley & Sons, Inc. (“Wiley”), relating to the licensing of Wiley Online Library; and
All related terms and conditions, terms of service, amendments, addenda, appendices, attachments, product terms, MOUs, MOAs, data processing agreements, and/or letters of intent; and
All financial documents or records of financial transactions, exchanges or obligations with language governing the use of the Wiley Online Library.
Responsive materials include all contracts, agreements, amendments, appendices, invoices, and any other documents listed above that incorporate language governing terms of use of the Wiley Online Library.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 calendar days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

mo

communications.subject: Re: Public Records Request

Regards,

Suzan Phillips Brown
Staff Attorney

communications.communication:

A. Emails containing the non-case sensitive keyword: "Yad Vashem" sent or received by any of the following individuals between March 1, 2022 & May 15, 2022:
   1. Menashe Shapiro

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Russel Neiss

communications.subject: Texas Public Information Act Request: Traffic stop
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Texas Public Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

I am seeking the following information regarding a traffic stop conducted on September 6th late night and/or September 7th early morning hours, within the city limits of Laredo,Texas. 
subject involved
Harrison Byars
DOB 11/30/1985
Citations issued-
Driving without CDL
driving without headlights
The records being sought are the following
Any and all dispatch logs, police blotters, logs, reports, documents, gathered, filed, and/or transferred in relation to this traffic stop. With all relevant and applicable public information surrounding the reasons for the stop, the time duration of the stop, any and all reports made in relation to the results of the traffic stop.

I am also requesting any and all audio recordings, dash cam recording and/or video footage from the traffic stop by each officer involved in the traffic stop. 

I am also requesting any and all body worn audio and or video information obtained by the officer or officers involved in this traffic stop from the initial dispatch contact and or initial contact made with Harrison Byars through and for the entirety of the traffic stop.


eff. January 1, 2025.
Art. 2B.0112.
RELEASE OF INFORMATION RECORDED BY BODY WORN
CAMERA.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Allison

communications.subject: Open Records Request :: W040284-033125
communications.communication:
Welcome to the City of Laredo Open Records Center. We have received your Public Information Request, and it has been diverted to the appropriate department for processing. Pursuant to the Public Information Act, the governmental body will try to complete the request within a reasonable amount of time depending on the nature of the request. However, you can expect to receive notification should the request require more than 10 business days to complete. 

Please note, the Texas Public Information Act does not require a governmental body to create new information, to do legal research, or to answer questions. The request must ask for records or information already in existence. In addition, the City of Laredo may collect a fee as prescribed by law or regulation for the requested documents. If a fee is not prescribed by law or regulation, the fee shall be the actual cost of duplicating the record(s) and any applicable labor costs. 

Finally, you can monitor the progress of your request through the automated open records center on the City of Laredo website .  Unfortunately, this email is an automated notification, which is unable to receive replies. Therefore, if you have any questions with respect to a pending request or pertaining to any open records issue,  you may directly contact this office through the open records center.  You may also reach us by phone at the number below. 

Very truly yours, 

City Attorney's Office 
Public Information Coordinator for the City of Laredo 
1110 Houston Street 
City Hall, 3rd Floor 
Laredo, Texas 78040 
(956) 791-7319 Telephone 
(956) 791-7494 Facsimile

title: Animal Cruelty Evidence Related to PBSO Case #06-25044752

communications.subject: Florida Sunshine Law Request: Animal Cruelty Evidence Related to PBSO Case #06-25044752
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Florida Sunshine Law, I hereby request the following records:

I am submitting a formal request for access to and copies of all body worn camera (BWC) and in-car camera (ICC) footage, as well as video and photographic evidence related to the below-detailed incident:
 * Palm Beach County Sheriff's Office (PBSO) Case Number: 06-25044752
 * Nature of Incident: Animal Cruelty
 * Date of Incident/Arrest: March 28, 2025 (arrest date - incident occurred on or about March 19-20, 2025)
 * Time of Arrest: 07:40 hours
 * Location of Arrest: 8559 Boca Rio Rd, Boca Raton, FL 33433
 * Arresting Officer(s): Detective Eric Zadanosky and Deputy Sheriff Derek Harrison (identified from narrative)
 * Defendant: Gabriel Gustavo Martinez, Date of Birth: 08/19/1990
 * Victim: Matthew Avoletta
 * Animal Victim: Gypsy

This request specifically includes, but is not limited to:
1.  All BWC and ICC footage from:
    * Detective Eric Zadanosky
    * Deputy Sheriff Derek Harrison
    * Any other PBSO personnel present at the scene of the arrest, transport, or interaction with Gabriel Gustavo Martinez on March 28, 2025, related to Case #06-25044752.

        * To ensure a comprehensive search, please include footage from:
        * The time of initial contact with Gabriel Gustavo Martinez at 8559 Boca Rio Rd
        * The arrest of Gabriel Gustavo Martinez

        * The transport of Gabriel Gustavo Martinez to the PBSO District 7 substation

        * Any interactions with Gabriel Gustavo Martinez at the substation

        * The transport of Gabriel Gustavo Martinez to West Boca Medical Center

2. Any and all video footage of the alleged animal cruelty incident involving Gabriel Gustavo Martinez and Gypsy, as referenced in the case narrative.

3. All still photographs of Gypsy's injuries, as referenced in the case narrative.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days.

Sincerely,

Jonathan Colon
